{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6bcd9d9a-1d21-4922-9cba-df1e8a2e2c89","content":"Replace `[ExpectedException]` with `Assert.ThrowsException<T>`, which is more precise — it verifies *which line* throws:\n\n```csharp\n[TestMethod]\npublic void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()\n{\n    var service = new UserService();\n\n    Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n        () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\n}\n```\n\n**Why?** `[ExpectedException]` passes if *any* line in the test throws, masking bugs. `Assert.ThrowsException` scopes the assertion to the exact call.\n\n**MSTest v4+:** Use `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>` instead — it's the renamed/preferred API and `ExpectedExceptionAttribute` is removed entirely.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"be35e07d-7b1d-4aac-ad7a-344f532031ec","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about modernizing a test that uses `[ExpectedException]` in MSTest. This is a well-known test modernization pattern - replacing `[ExpectedException]` with `Assert.ThrowsException` (or `Assert.ThrowsExactly` in MSTest v4+).\n\nI don't need to invoke a skill for this - it's a straightforward question I can answer directly.","outputTokens":300,"requestId":"1BC8:49329:4B9386:561DEC:6A03D632"},"id":"ea257084-6ac3-49a1-9dc1-319995978a48","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:39:06.109Z","parentId":"56041927-f044-4b85-af79-4b9b5bc4d3f4"}
